<DOC><DOCNO> AP880220-0128 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-20-88 0122EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Thailand-Laos     02-20 0313</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Thailand-Laos,0320</SECOND><HEAD>Truce Begins In Disputed Border Area</HEAD><BYLINE>By MOLLY YONG</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Thai and Laotian forces began a trucein a disputed border area Friday, pulling back from the hillyground where hundreds of comrades had been killed since November,Thai officers said.   After the cease-fire began at 8 a.m., two parallel rows of Thaiand Laotian flags were planted to mark a zone two miles deep thatsoldiers are forbidden to cross, said the army chief of staff, Gen.Charuay Wongsayant.   Military officials of both sides agreed to the cease-fireWednesday after two days of talks in Bangkok. The disputed area isabout 240 miles north of Bangkok between Thailand's northernprovince of Phitsanulok and Sayaboury province in Laos.   Col. Rithee Rungkaputi, chief of civilian affairs for the 3rdArmy Region, said a half-hour skirmish occurred on a contested hillan hour before the truce began, with no casualties. He said itthere probably was a delay in commmunicating the cease-fire order.   Rithee also reported a heavy artillery exchange and two groundbattles Wednesday and Thursday, while military teams from the twocountries were meeting in Bangkok.   Foreign Minister Siddhi Savetsila of Thailand told reportersFriday that Foreign Ministry officials had been sent to Franceseeking help in resolving the problem. Both sides claim the area onthe basis of recognized maps and a 1907 French-Thai treaty.   The official Laotian news agency KPL quoted Maj. Gen. ThonglayKommasith, deputy head of the army's general political department,as saying the talks in Bangkok ``paved the way toward negotiations,a diplomatic channel to solve the Lao-Thai border problem.''   Thonglay participated in the Bangkok meeting. The dispatch saidhe spoke at a news conference Thursday in Vientiane.   The agreement calls for the governments to hold talks within 15days after the truce begins to determine the frontier line.</TEXT></DOC>